<emphasis id="B9706466BB3EC8597DFDF9B12A46C81E" box="[185,308,1609,1635]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="244" reason="1">Diagnosis</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB3EC8597C06F9B32976C819" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[322,516,1610,1636]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alamosa">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB3EC8597C06F9B32976C819" box="[322,516,1610,1636]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="244">Hypotrix alamosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(forewing length 
<quantity id="4CFC1591BB3EC8597F97F9B22824C819" box="[723,854,1610,1636]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="1.4" pageId="19" pageNumber="244" unit="mm" value="15.0" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="14.0">14–16 mm</quantity>
) occurs in two forms. In the darker, more common form (Fig. 10) the forewing is reddish brown with the
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBBB874BB39C85E7DC8FC422B98CD8D" blockId="20.[140,1108,954,1008]" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7DC8FC422A42CDAD" bold="true" box="[140,304,954,976]" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">Figures 46–48.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB39C85E7C72FC432AF5CDAD" authorityName="Guenee" authorityYear="1852" box="[310,391,955,976]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7C72FC432AF5CDAD" box="[310,391,955,976]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">Hypotrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB39C85E7CF3FC43296ECDAD" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" box="[439,540,955,976]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Anhypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7CF3FC43296ECDAD" box="[439,540,955,976]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">Anhypotrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
male genitalia. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7FF6FC4229BFCDAD" bold="true" box="[690,717,954,976]" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">46</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB39C85E7F97FC43285CCDAD" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1906" box="[723,814,955,976]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Ursogastra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lunata">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7F97FC432994CDAD" box="[723,742,955,976]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7FB7FC43285CCDAD" box="[755,814,955,976]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">lunata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7E71FC422822CDAD" bold="true" box="[821,848,954,976]" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">47</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB39C85E7E12FC432892CDAD" authorityName="Guenee" authorityYear="1852" box="[854,992,955,976]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="purpurigera">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7E12FC43281ACDAD" box="[854,872,955,976]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7E31FC432892CDAD" box="[885,992,955,976]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">purpurigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7EA2FC422F73CDAD" bold="true" box="[998,1025,954,976]" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">48</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB39C85E794CFC432B96CD8D" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes &amp; McDunnough" baseAuthorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Anhypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tristis">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E794CFC432B96CD8D" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">Anhypotrix tristis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBBB874BB39C85E7DC8FBC22F21C8FA" blockId="20.[140,1108,1082,1672]" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">
maculation sharply defined by dark-red lines. Th e medial area is similar in color to the remainder of the forewing and the postmedial line touches, or almost touches, the reniform spot. Superficially this form is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB39C85E7E4EFB7928C2CAE7" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[778,944,1152,1178]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hueco">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7E4EFB7928C2CAE7" box="[778,944,1152,1178]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">Hypotrix hueco</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see under 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB39C85E7972FB792BBBCAC0" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hueco">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7972FB792F3ECAE7" box="[1078,1100,1153,1178]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7DC8FB5B2BBBCAC0" box="[140,201,1187,1213]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">hueco</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB39C85E7C4EFB5C2A88CAC3" authority="(Smith)" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1898" box="[266,506,1187,1214]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Xestia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bolteri">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7C4EFB5C2AEBCAC0" box="[266,409,1187,1213]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">Xestia bolteri</emphasis>
(Smith)
</taxonomicName>
, both of which occur with 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB39C85E7E6FFB5C28D5CAC0" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[811,935,1187,1214]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alamosa">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7E6FFB5C2833CAC0" box="[811,833,1188,1213]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7E0BFB5B28D5CAC0" box="[847,935,1187,1213]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">alamosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB39C85E7DC8FB3F2A6ECA9C" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1898" box="[140,284,1223,1249]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Xestia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bolteri">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7DC8FB3F2A6ECA9C" box="[140,284,1223,1249]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">Xestia bolteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in that 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB39C85E7C33FB3F2A87CA9C" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[375,501,1223,1249]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alamosa">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7C33FB3F2AFFCA9D" box="[375,397,1223,1248]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7CD9FB3F2A87CA9C" box="[413,501,1223,1249]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">alamosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has smaller reniform, orbicular, and claviform spots, and in lacking spiniform setae on the tibiae; 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB39C85E7FCAFB13286CCB79" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1898" box="[654,798,1258,1284]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Xestia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bolteri">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7FCAFB13286CCB79" box="[654,798,1258,1284]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">Xestia bolteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is illustrated in 
<bibRefCitation id="EF95C585BB39C85E7E9CFB122BB9CB5A" author="Lafontaine JD" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" refId="ref13914" refString="Lafontaine JD (1998) Noctuoidea, Noctuidae (part), Noctuinae (part - Noctuini). In: Dominick et al. (Eds) Th e Moths of America North of Mexico fasc. 27.3. The Wedge Entomological Research Foundation, Washington, 348 pp." type="book" year="1998">Lafontaine 1998</bibRefCitation>
. Th e pale form of 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB39C85E7CF4FAF62943CB5A" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[432,561,1293,1320]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alamosa">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7CF4FAF62AB4CB5A" box="[432,454,1294,1319]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7C9DFAF52943CB5A" box="[473,561,1293,1319]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">alamosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
looks like the specimens have been bleached, so the forewing is light orange with the maculation weakly defined by fine yellow lines. Th e dark and light forms frequently occur together and the two 
<typeStatus id="54BF06D6BB39C85E7EEAFAAC2F7DCB13" box="[942,1039,1364,1390]" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">syntypes</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB39C85E7972FAAC2B96CBEC" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alamosa">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7972FAAC2F3ECB10" box="[1078,1100,1364,1389]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7DC8FA8F2B96CBEC" box="[140,228,1399,1425]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">alamosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
represent a specimen of each form. The 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7F82FA8F2816CBEC" box="[710,868,1399,1425]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">male genitalia</emphasis>
differ from those of other species in many features: the valves are tapered from the base to apex a slightly indented “neck” at the base of the triangular cucullus; the sacculus is very large with a rounded lobe projecting from the dorsal margin and the membranous saccular flap overtops almost the entire sclerotized part; the digitus is wide and truncated apically; the apical half of the uncus is broad and spatulate; the vesica has a mass of cornuti near the apex of the aedeagus, and the apical part of the vesica has four tight coils. In the 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB39C85E7DFDF9952A1AC8FA" box="[185,360,1645,1671]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">female genitalia</emphasis>
the appendix bursae has four tight coils, corresponding to those
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBBB874BB38C85F7DC8FF5F2A38CE99" blockId="21.[140,1108,167,333]" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">in the vesica, and the ductus bursae is heavily sclerotized with a prominent posterior bulge to the left.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31EEBFFBB38C85F7DFDFF152A62CF30" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BBBB874BB38C85F7DFDFF152A62CF30" blockId="21.[140,1108,167,333]" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7DFDFF152A8FCF7A" bold="true" box="[185,509,237,263]" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7DFDFF152A25CF7A" box="[185,343,237,263]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" reason="1">Distribution</emphasis>
and biology.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB38C85F7F4CFF1629A0CF7A" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[520,722,237,263]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alamosa">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7F4CFF1629A0CF7A" box="[520,722,237,263]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">Hypotrix alamosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in known only from southeastern 
<collectingRegion id="49C07696BB38C85F7DF8FEE82A6ECF57" box="[188,284,272,298]" country="United States of America" name="Arizona" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">Arizona</collectingRegion>
. Collecting dates range from early June to mid-July and early to late September.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
